messages.text: I need to talk to you, Dr. Owens.
Brooke?
Is everything OK?
No.
I think Ethan's having some kind of mental breakdown.
What do you mean?
I saw him in my office this morning and he seemed fine.
He asked you about the diary on your desk, right?
Yes. Why?
He thinks he's cursed because of something in that notebook.
And he's afraid to tell you.
He thinks you'll have him committed to a psych ward.
What? Why?
Because of his mom.
Oh, I see. Tell me what's going on.
He went AWOL for a few hours.
When he finally responded to my texts, he wasn’t speaking English anymore.
I think it's Latin.
I'm freaked out.
He's texting you in Latin?
Yeah.
He told me earlier he spoke Latin in his sleep—
That he was saying the same phrase over and over again.
He's texting it to me now.
What's he saying?
"Facium ut mei memineris."
He told me it means something like, "You will remember me."
Good God.
What?
I took the diary to work to look into it.
I consulted with some of my colleagues at the museum and it seems to be authentic.
It belonged to a woman named Della Dossett.
Yeah. Ethan told me that when he was still speaking English.
But he said no one knew who she was.
Well, today we found an article about her in our online database services.
It looks like she was executed in 1808 by a lynch mob for the murder of Theodore Tate.
But there was no notation in the article about the connection between Della and Tate.
Della’s last words were, "Facium ut mei memineris."
That’s Latin for, "I'll make you remember me."
OMG. Seriously?!
The article was very old and extremely hard to track down.
I don't see how Ethan could've known what she’d said.
I've scoured the diary and that phrase isn't in it.
Who was Theodore Tate?
He was a banker in New York City.
But his death seemed very strange to me.
What do you mean?
It looks like it was a suicide.
According to the article, he'd been showing symptoms of mental illness prior to his death—hallucinations, delusions.
He even had convulsions similar to a seizure, but the doctors were at a loss.
Then he drowned himself in the Hudson River.
Known at the time as the North River.
But why was Della hanged if it was a suicide?
Apparently, Tate’s neighbors said they saw her enter his house a week before he died.
And some other witnesses claimed to have seen her lurking by the river the night he drowned.
But, like I said, it was unclear how they were actually acquainted.
That’s so messed up.
I’m afraid it gets worse.
When his body was recovered, he had a geometric occult symbol carved into his chest.
Based on the symbol and on Tate's earlier symptoms, his peers accused Della Dossett of witchcraft.
They tracked her down.
They broke into her home and found a bloody ice pick in her living room.
And in her bedroom, they found a diary that included a sketch of the very symbol that was carved into Tate's chest.
The next morning, she was summarily executed by the vigilantes.
Were there dolls in her house, too?
Porcelain dolls, with no eyes?
Well, yes, actually.
Their eyes seemed to have been poked out by the ice pick.
The dolls were untouched and full of spiders.
How did you know about them?
Ethan hallucinated, just like Tate did.
And he said he had visions of the dolls.
Dr. Owens, I think Ethan’s under Della’s curse.
No, Brooke. There's no curse.
There has to be some rational explanation for Ethan's behavior.
I'm going to get him the help he needs.
IDK, it sounds like Della used the symbol to mind-control Theodore Tate.
I bet she forced him to commit suicide.
And now she's got Ethan!
Brooke, my colleagues and I have been pouring through the diary for hours.
We've all seen the symbols in it, and we're fine.
But Ethan got that stupid symbol tattooed on his arm a few days ago.
I see. I will be having a talk with him about the tattoo.
Yeah, because it cursed him!
No, because he shouldn’t be making permanent marks on his body.
There's no such thing as a curse or magic mind-control.
Dr. Owens, please!
He needs help but I'm stuck on the mountain with my family 'til tomorrow.
OK. I'll go home to check on Ethan.
But why did Della Dossett use a symbol to control Theodore Tate?
How did they know each other? And why did she want him to commit suicide?!
I don't know, Brooke.
We gotta find out, for Ethan's sake. Please.
OK. Calm down.
I'll look for more information on Della Dossett.
But first, I need to call Ethan to tell him I'm coming home.
I'll get back to you soon.
31 minutes later.
Dick?
Your boy Ethan's been asking me all kinds of questions about the diary I gave you.
I know. He thinks he's cursed because of a symbol he found in it.
He hasn't been answering my phone calls, but I'm going home to check on him.
If I can ever get out of the stand-still traffic on the interstate…
I'm concerned Ethan may have a mental health issue.
I'm sorry he's involved you.
It's no bother.
I've been looking into Della Dossett ever since he texted me earlier.
I have to say, I'm intrigued by the mystery behind it all.
I am, too.
I've only found one newspaper article about her so far.
It was very detailed, but I think it raised more questions than it answered.
Well, my husband Adam's into genealogy, so he looked up the Dossetts in the early 1800s.
He found Della's obituary scanned in online.
She lived from 1793—1808, and died at age 15.
Yes. We discovered she was hanged for witchcraft.
Exactly. Did you find the obit for Clara Dossett, too?
1774—1796. Survived by her daughter, Della.
So Della's mother died when she was 3.
But how does that help us?
Some of these 1800s obits include more gratuitous detail than the papers do these days.
Clara's says she committed suicide by drowning herself in the Hudson River.
Just like my ancestor Cornelius Finch did after he found Della's diary.
And a well-to-do New York banker named Theodore Tate.
Theodore Tate?
Yes. He drowned himself in the Hudson in 1808, and Della Dossett was executed for his murder.
The government stopped executing witches in the 1700s, but the mob had a mind of its own.
They took justice into their own hands.
But we weren’t able to find any connection between Della and Tate.
I think I can help you with that.
Go on…
Well, Adam and I tried to find Clara Dossett’s marriage license.
We looked through the records from 1789—1793.
Because Clara turned 15 in 1789 and Della was born in 1793.
Ingenious. Did you find anything?
Nothing.
It seems like Clara Dossett gave birth to Della out of wedlock.
However, we searched for Della's birth certificate in the census records, too.
You know, to find out who the father was.
Wait.
Are you saying what I think you're saying, Finch?
Yeah, I am.
Della's father was, like you said, a well-to-do New York banker.
His name was Theodore Tate.
